name="doi">10.1007/978-3-642-54830-7_26</fr:meta></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:p>We characterise the polarised evaluation order through a categorical structure where the hypothesis that composition is associative is relaxed. Duploid is the name of the structure, as a reference to Jean-Louis Loday’s duplicial algebras. The main result is a reflection <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\textit {Adj}\to \textit {Dupl}]]></fr:tex> where <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\textit {Dupl}]]></fr:tex> is a category of duploids and duploid functors, and <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\textit {Adj}]]></fr:tex> is the category of adjunctions and pseudo maps of adjunctions. The result suggests that the various biases in denotational semantics: indirect, call-by-value, call-by-name… are a way of hiding the fact that composition is not always associative.</fr:p></fr:mainmatter></fr:tree></fr:mainmatter></fr:tree><fr:tree
